      "side": 1,
      "message": "I dug into whether a more principled fix is possible; I believe this is the principled place, and I\u0027ve expanded the comment to justify it.\n\nThe underlying problem is that the machinery below evaluates the let\u0027s expression in a synthetic vertex, i.e. it unifies whatever the expression yields into a fresh child node. For `let X \u003d self` the expression yields the enclosing vertex itself, so this unifies a parent into its own child, and the resulting expansion can never be a faithful copy: it re-instantiates the parent\u0027s StructLits with the synthetic vertex as `self`, so nested references through the let rebind to the copy. In the rooted case this is masked because the synthetic vertex structure-shares the parent; for inline vertices sharing is disabled (issue 3801), exposing the mirror path.\n\nI also prototyped fixing this in the sharing layer instead, by allowing dynamic/non-rooted arcs to be shared into let vertices. That fixes the single-conjunct test case but not the two-conjunct one: sharing can always fall back to expansion (unshare on a second conjunct arriving via notifications, and sharing of let-labeled referents is itself unsupported), and the expansion rebinds self as above. Since sharing must remain a semantically optional optimization, alias transparency cannot be guaranteed there.\n\nWhat makes ValueReference special rather than an arbitrary syntactic carve-out: it is the one expression class whose value is defined as a vertex identity and whose resolution is a total environment lookup (relNode) that can never suspend or be incomplete. Every other let expression genuinely needs the synthetic vertex as a caching and suspension point, and resolving those referents directly would change incomplete-error and structural-cycle behavior.",
